 Let the total number of pennies in Joyce's bank be represented by {eq}x{/eq}.


At first, she counts them by fives, so we have  
\begin{align*}
x & \equiv 1 \pmod{5}\\
\end{align*} 
At the same time, she also counts them by threes, finding that there are two left over after being divided by three.  We have
\begin{align*}
x & \equiv 2 \pmod{3}\\
\end{align*} 
To simplify this situation, we set {eq}x = k + 2 {/eq}, where {eq}k{/eq} is the multiple of three. If we compare this with the first condition, we get {eq}x {/eq} as {eq}k = 3i + 1{/eq}.  
\begin{align*}
k & = 3i + 1\\
x & = 3i + 1 + 2\\
x & = 3i + 3\\
x & = 3(i + 1)\\
x & = 3m \;(\text{where }m \ge 1)\\
\end{align*} 
Now, recognizing that {eq}x = 3m{/eq} satisfies both given conditions (i.e., leaving a remainder of {eq}1{/eq} when divided by {eq}5{/eq} and a remainder of {eq}2{/eq} when the same number is divided by {eq}3{/eq}),
we find the smallest possible value of {eq}m{/eq} to be the smallest positive integer. {eq}m = 1{/eq} satisfies the conditions (resulting in {eq}x = 3{/eq}, a multiple of 3, removed pencil left). The minimum number of pencils {eq}x{/eq} in Joyce's bank is {eq}x = 9{/eq}. quod erat demonstrandum.

problem:
Chuck the llama is tied to the corner of a $2\text{ m}$ by $3\text{ m}$ shed on a $3\text{ m}$ leash. How much area (in square meters) does Chuck have in which to play if he can go only around the outside of the shed? [asy]
draw((0,0)--(15,0)--(15,10)--(0,10)--cycle,black+linewidth(1));
draw((15,10)--(27,19),black+linewidth(1));
dot((27,19));
label("Shed",(7.5,5));
label("CHUCK",(27,19),N);
label("2",(0,0)--(0,10),W);
label("3",(0,0)--(15,0),S);
label("3",(15,10)--(27,19),SE);
[/asy]

solution:
When Chuck has the leash extended to its full length, he can move in a $270^\circ$ arc, or $\frac{3}{4}$ of a full circle about the point where the leash is attached. (He is blocked from going further by the shed.)

[asy]
draw((0,0)--(15,0)--(15,10)--(0,10)--cycle,black+linewidth(1));
draw((15,10)--(27,19),black+linewidth(1));
dot((27,19));
label("Shed",(7.5,5));
label("2",(0,0)--(0,10),W);
label("3",(0,0)--(15,0),S);
label("3",(15,10)--(27,19),SE);
draw((0,10)..(3,19)..(6,22)..(24,22)..(27,19)..(30,10)..(27,1)..(24,-2)..(15,-5),black+linewidth(1)+dashed);
draw((15,0)--(15,-5),black+linewidth(1)+dashed);
[/asy]

The area that he can play inside this circle is $\frac{3}{4}$ of the area of a full circle of radius $3,$ or $$\frac{3}{4}\times \pi(3^2)=\frac{27}{4}\pi.$$ When the leash is extended fully to the left, Chuck just reaches the top left corner of the shed, so can go no further. When the leash is extended fully to the bottom, Chuck's leash extends $1\text{ m}$ below the length of the shed. This means that Chuck can play in more area to the left.

[asy]
draw((0,0)--(15,0)--(15,10)--(0,10)--cycle,black+linewidth(1));
draw((15,10)--(27,19),black+linewidth(1));
dot((27,19));
label("Shed",(7.5,5));
label("2",(0,0)--(0,10),W);
label("3",(15,10)--(27,19),SE);
draw((0,10)..(3,19)..(6,22)..(24,22)..(27,19)..(30,10)..(27,1)..(24,-2)..(15,-5),black+linewidth(1)+dashed);
draw((15,0)--(15,-5),black+linewidth(1)+dashed);
draw((15,-5)..(11.4645,-3.5355)..(10,0),black+linewidth(1)+dashed);
label("1",(15,0)--(15,-5),W);
label("2",(15,0)--(15,10),E);
label("3",(0,10)--(15,10),N);
[/asy]

This area is a $90^\circ$ sector of a circle of radius $1,$ or $\frac{1}{4}$ of this circle.  So this additional area is $$\frac{1}{4} \times \pi (1^2)=\frac{1}{4}\pi.$$ So the total area that Chuck has in which to play is $$\frac{27}{4}\pi + \frac{1}{4}\pi = \frac{28}{4}\pi = \boxed{7\pi}\text{ m}^2.$$

